Russian President Vladimir Putin has signed a law on the introduction of administrative liability for violation of the deadline and procedure for payment of goods (works, services) when making purchases for state and municipal needs.
This law is intended to address the very acute problem of non-fulfillment of its obligations by customers in the implementation of public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, a situation where entrepreneurs could not receive payment under already fulfilled state and municipal contracts was ubiquitous.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General’s Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers, who concluded contracts not backed by financing, tried in every way to avoid payment obligations and included illegal conditions in the contracts.
The problem was systemic throughout the country.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the Prosecutor’s Office has submitted 9.7 thousand submissions, as a result of their consideration, 4.5 thousand officials have been involved in disciplinary responsibility, 533 administrative officials have been involved, and the investigative bodies for the organization of procedural checks have submitted 75 materials.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles was repaid.
And these huge sums were accumulated far from the result of non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
The fabulous debts resulted in numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts.
Here's a case in point.
The head of a small company won a competition to provide social transportation services for several million rubles.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is a growing financial coma of debts on wages, taxes, loans, which would lead to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur did not seek help from the prosecutor's office.
In some regions, the problem has been minimized.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, identified by the prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt ratios continue to reach critical levels, the prosecutor’s office operates under manual anti-crisis management.
The Prosecutor-General personally conducts field meetings with representatives of the local authorities, where all violations discovered by prosecutors and measures to eliminate them are examined in detail.
Such operational meetings have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of the Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences in respect of the Establishment of Administrative Responsibility of the Officials of the Customer for Violation of the Term and Procedure of Payment of Goods (Work, Services) for the Implemented by the President shall be able to qualitatively improve the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia at the initiative of the Prosecutor General’s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for the violation by the official of the customer of the term and procedure of payment of goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
And if an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he will be disqualified for a period of one year to two years.
All prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative novelties in practice.
The Civil Rights Protection Group has issued a travel warning in Missouri.
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group’s statement reads as follows: “The National Association for the Advancement of Travelers of All Colored Territories, valid until August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, guests and citizens of the State of Missouri to be especially careful and to exercise increased caution when traveling around the state in conjunction with non-state travel.”
According to the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population, the group’s announcement of a travel warning was prompted by a recently passed law in Missouri that made it harder for people to win discrimination-related lawsuits, as well as the fact that state law enforcement agencies disproportionately often choose their targets as representatives of misogyny.
“You have people who are violating human rights.
They are stopped on the roads because of the color of their skin, they are beaten and killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population of Missouri, told the Kansas City Star newspaper.
“We hear complaints more often than ever before.”
This is the first warning of its kind, announced by the organization in relation to the U.S. state.
The group cited incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of twenty-eight-year-old Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas during a state visit, and the Missouri State Police arrested him without charging him with a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri State Attorney General’s Office that the likelihood of being stopped on the road for black drivers is 75 percent higher than for whites.
“The goal of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri,” he said.
“People should be prepared in one way or another, whether they take the money with them for a deposit or tell relatives that they are traveling across the state.”
According to the latest data from the FBI’s Hate Crime Reporting Program, 100 hate crimes were registered in Missouri in 2015, making the state the 16th in the state in the number of such violations.
Also, the travel warning is a response to the new Missouri law, after which it will be more difficult to bring a case against a legal entity in connection with housing or labor discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) announced warnings for travelers to Texas and Arizona after these states passed new immigration control laws that ordered local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which, according to the ACLU, should have increased the number of convictions.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
