Now the Trump White House has targeted the Statue of Liberty.
The most reliable sign of regime change is when he begins to fight statues.
Americans understand this no worse than everyone else – hence the deliberate theatrical demolition of the statue of Saddam Hussein on Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologues of the Trump administration, no doubt knew what he was doing when he carried a symbolic axe over the Statue of Liberty during a fierce dispute with CNN journalist Jim Acosta over the president’s proposals to sharply reduce legal migration.
Let's be honest, Miller didn't try the statue itself.
Countless owners of pleasure ships and artists depicting the Statue of Liberty would have lynched him if he had tried to do so.
But he tried to make sense of it, and especially of the meaning attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument, when the poems of Emma Lazarus were added to the pedestal.
“I don’t want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is ... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you are talking about was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty.
Miller put the facts right, but as he himself said, it’s not really about the story.
This is about the current sounding of the striking words of Lazarus, the only ones in which the state invites not any immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds, dreaming to breathe freely, / The unfortunate throws of your abundant shores."
Never before have “unfortunate throws” been so visible on our screens.
Miller was not engaged in literary studies - he made it clear that in America Trump these people are not expected.
This dispute over the meaning of the statue is part of a broader political and cultural war: it is indeed a dispute over the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends, who fought to place her words on the base of the statue after her death - understood very well that they were committing a completely political act.
The sculpture was intended to mark the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female image of Liberty.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a very different name: The Mother of the Exiles.
The combination of poetry and image was a brilliant feminist movement and a crushing attack on American nativism.
And how Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right though to change it back.
Rash Limbo, a kind of John the Baptist who heralded the coming of Trump, reasoned in 2010 that Freedom does not invite anyone, rather it is an early neoconservative who carries the flame of America to the dark world: “Freedom goes forward.
It carries a torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to light the way to the United States.”
Against the custom Limbo really got to the point here.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
The great creative achievement of Lazarus was to see her as she would be seen by the exhausted, unhappy, but hopeful people on the decks of ships after a long and often difficult voyage.
It means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people who are looking for refuge and a chance for a better life.
Her statue answers them with words of hope and hospitality that they dream of hearing.
And, of course, this is not the prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is not to light the way, but to inflame hatred, which is the only source of their power.
