Blocking critics on Facebook: Don’t run for public office if you’re not willing to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press was.
Americans loved George Washington, but that didn’t stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
His criticism, of course, irritated him.
But he didn’t shut his mouth to his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said, "It is possible to take away the freedom of speech and we, the deaf and dumb, will be led like sheep to the slaughter."
Now I’m going to move on to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s subordinates blocked and deleted posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called the lawsuit null and void, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "well and what."
“It’s just Facebook,” many would say.
But that's important, too.
And this is especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is an amazingly popular Republican governor in a mostly democratic state.
It is second in the approval rating among the 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He has demonstrated a firm hand in state administration and a commitment to its principles.
He also cleverly uses Facebook as the primary way to connect with his constituents and jokingly demonstrates on his page his bald head after chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor’s page – which is declared as an official public forum and is run by the administration’s employees for taxpayers’ money – is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with The Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the governor’s actions, arguing that blocking comments is simply a moderation.
But it’s too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers, and haters who are malicious on the Internet.
"Post" spoke to some of the real people that Hogan blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls, - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor, who turn to their elected leaders.
All of them say that their comments were respectful, substantive and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible as saying that Hogan was a Catholic.
Lakshmi’s lawyer Sarma Ramana of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
“I have written a polite comment that I am disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news,” she wrote in the comments section of the Post.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it’s a so-called screwdriver, rather than admitting that they’re dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens.”
What the governor’s subordinates call a “concentrated spam attack,” others would probably call an “active life position.”
In the age of Facebook, it’s easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
This is a much less dusty job than it used to be when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical front pages, or arresting and mouthing protesters.
But that’s exactly what’s happening now, only in numbers.
Hohen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social networks.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, twisty decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James K. Casheris of Alexandria, the chairman of the Laudon County Supervisory Board violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from his Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bevin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington’s day, the era of affordable postal spending has made about the same upheaval as today’s Internet.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers grew fourfold, and the authors of anonymous letters greatly eroded his authority.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the aliases “Yurikola”, “Valerius”, “Belizarius” and “Porcius” wrote letters to newspapers mocking Washington’s decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the online project "George Washington Documents", his office was flooded with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Trade and Navigation.
But he didn’t try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing with that.
