Poverty and death in Indonesia's 'golden land'
After lunch, Bardina Degei does not use a plate.
It is rarely used even in pots.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Panay County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually simply places a sweet potato, which here is called a “note”, right in the center.
After half an hour, the charred tubers are harvested and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the ground floor – she has no furniture – and it is here that she does her housework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet serves a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, so she was not allowed to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
“No one decides to walk around the village after five in the evening,” she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, publicly raising their hands in front of the occupying troops.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the government of Jakarta, which maintains tight control over the region without allowing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jaipur, the administrative center of the province, to Nairobi, and then a five-hour shake by rental car.
There is no public transport here.
The city, with a population of about 19,000, consists of wooden houses lined with bamboo fences; corrugated steel roofs are painted with rust in a variety of reddish hues.
Few Indonesians came here, let alone journalists, and almost no foreigners.
Prior to the arrival of the Christian missionaries, the Papuan mee pago worshiped a god named Uga Tame.
There were other changes.
“It was unusual for us to wear these clothes,” Degey says, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
“We used to only wear leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
It is also the Indonesian Golden Land.
The world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Panay, a high-altitude province roughly the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua can boast of forest reserves, the cost of which is estimated at $ 78 billion.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia’s powerful armed forces maintain their stifling presence here.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local servicemen and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this golden vein and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights defenders, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and deprived of their liberty.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, mass killings in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the 1970s can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything”, a report published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – especially frequent, as claimed in another report, rape and electric shock.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because the incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
Hedges have been delayed as Papuan resources have attracted inflows of IDPs from other parts of Indonesia.
The province’s 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javan stews, "warungi", sell fried chicken and a mixture of vegetables "gado-gado", served with peanut sauce.
Locals are trying to keep up with the competition.
“Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables cheaper than the natives of Papua in the traditional market,” explains Abet Yoo, a twenty-four-year-old native of Panay who moved to Jayapura, the administrative center of the province, because of work.
“Because of this, the indigenous inhabitants of Papua – the mother-moms (women) of Papua – have lost their market.”
Indonesian President Joko Vidodo, known to the people as Jokovi, has vowed to tackle inequality and human rights violations in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, a former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua’s 29 districts, including Panay.
But in Papua, almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel loyal.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice,” Yoo said.
In fact, only two months after the October inauguration of Jokowi Panay survived the tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were on the street singing Christmas hymns at a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers pulled out of the darkness on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them to turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Javadt Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who were drunk chased children and beat them with rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus Eimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to the nearby government building of the election commission, and the next day the situation worsened.
About 1,000 Papuan men, women and children gathered at a soccer field in front of a local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed waita, a dance of the Papuan tribe mee pago: running around in circles and depicting birdsong.
Some protesters began to throw stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation escalated, the soldiers on the internal radio were ordered: “If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them”, – so it sounded, as claimed in the official document, which was seen by the correspondents of the magazine “TIME”, but which was not published in the local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Jeremias Kayame, the head of the Quego Coto district in Enarotali, felt the approaching danger and called for calm, asking the crowd to disperse around the houses.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned around, I suddenly had a bullet in my left wrist,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still does not know who fired the shot, but says that the bullet came from the side of the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
The local resident Alfius Youwa was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johannes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told TIME.
“I saw that he was dead... I kissed him.”
General Yotje Mende, Papua’s senior police inspector, told reporters that his officers were only “protecting” their base because it was under attack.
“We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” said Commissioner Pujo Sulistio, a spokesman for the Papuan police in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
The news of the killings reached Jakarta only the next day.
Three weeks later, Djokovic delivered a fiery speech in Jaipur in which he expressed his condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the issue of historical abuses of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately, so that it will never happen again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Viranto said he would set up a non-judicial organization to end historic human rights violations.
But they almost immediately apologized.
“Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the 90s or early zeros.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be followed,” he said.
Viranto then gave up his words, speaking to TIME magazine in Jakarta on June 5, and said he did not plan to set up an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided through court.”
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of “crimes against humanity” over the deaths of more than 1,000 people during a bloody vote for East Timor’s independence in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been settled, including the Panay incident.
The families of the victims from Paniai met with such statements with gloomy distrust.
“I’ve been asked four times in the last three years, but there was absolutely no change,” says Johannes.
“I am tired.”
He says that years later he's still living in fear.
“I’m scared,” he says.
"I'm afraid I'll be arrested by the military, I'm afraid I'll be shot."
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the inhabitants of Paniai were afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came after me,” he says.
The shooting didn't stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired at villagers in the Deiyai district of Paniai.
In a clash between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to help take a man unconscious to the hospital, one person was killed and 17 others were injured, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Dow, drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the office of the construction site owned by the company.
According to police, residents of the village threw stones at officers, who in response fired warning shots.
But locals claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) started shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
“We were in such a panic, we’re afraid of retribution,” Domingu Badia, a 29-year-old man who lives near the hospital, told TIME magazine.
“I hid at home for two days.”
The Deiai parliament demanded that officers involved in the incident be called to account, and the mobile police brigade was withdrawn from the region.
Paniya has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development is a source of discontent among the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout the green-covered central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the “Free Papua Movement” (OPM), an insurgent army that claims to protect the rights of Papuans by staging sporadic attacks and raids with kidnappings of Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the senior OPM leaders come from Panay, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In response, in recent years, thousands of people in Panay have been arrested and unjustifiably detained by the military under the pretext of “protecting national independence”.
Some of them never came back.
Among the population of Papua, Panay is considered a “sad, forgotten place”.
Poverty intensifies discontent.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for locals.
Bread is not available to the same extent.
People here grow everything they eat: mostly nuts, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can take care of four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten club notes cost just 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, the economic inequality between indigenous Papuans and new migrants, who arrived in large numbers after the introduction of new flights to Nairobi airport, has increased.
Few existing vacancies are usually available to more educated and well-off migrants.
Papuans rarely have enough money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
“Young people don’t want to stay in the village ... because there’s no work and no money here,” said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the views of the rest of the world.
In addition, the restrictions on the work of the international media remain strict.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudi and Basil Longshan were deported from Papua for "insufficient coordination with the relevant organizations" despite being granted rare permissions to videotape.
According to Felim Keene, deputy director for Asia at Human Rights Watch, Jokowi’s campaign promises to lift media restrictions to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
“Foreign journalists trying to report from the insurgent eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua are now facing new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of attention from the press means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to Papua’s immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific nations – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands – appealed to the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “various and widespread violations” in Papua, including the shooting in Panay.
The same countries have supported the OPM in the past.
A spokesman for Indonesia’s Foreign Ministry, Arramanata Nasir, rejected the group’s statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that “Indonesia still has a democratic system and a free press, so it would be difficult to hide evidence of human rights violations.”
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by Dutch human rights ambassador Kijs Van Baar, visited Jaipur on 4 May, locals broke the silence, asking, “We want freedom,” as the source, who was also present at the meeting, claims, but wished to remain anonymous, said.
In Indonesia, there will be new presidential elections in 2019, but the Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Djokovic again.
“Jokovi is a man with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Panay shooting,” said Gobai, chairman of the tribe’s council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai, in addition to living in the shadow of the threat from the greedy army, are immersed in poverty, and their education and health care are in a miserable state.
Gobai says that the people of Panay, like the other Papuans, consider their vote given to Jokovi, a debt that he must pay.
“They don’t need money, they just want justice,” he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out the last symbolic act of disobedience: they buried the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly opposite the police and military plot.
Knowing that justice will probably never prevail, they will at least not allow the guilty to forget their crimes.
“They killed a member of our family,” says Jacobus, without raising his head.
“What else did we have to do?”
