EPA chief Pruitt refuses to delay implementation of Obama's emission reduction rules
The day after the 15-state lawsuit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency canceled his decision to postpone the implementation of Obama’s rules designed to reduce emissions of air-polluting substances that cause smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by saying that his agency now listens more than in previous administrations to the needs of the environmental regulators of individual states.
He did not mention the lawsuit against his previous position filed in the Federal Court of Appeal.
The dispute revolved around the October 1 deadline to which states must ensure compliance with the 2015 ozone standards at the ground level.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would delay their compliance for one year to give his department more time to study the plan and avoid “inconsistency with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth.”
Pruitt, who before being appointed by President Trump to his current position, was the attorney general of the state of Oklahoma, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tightening environmental standards.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or delayed the introduction of regulations that were opposed by the chemical or gas-oil industry.
An unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of the course taken by Peyton to return to the previous norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA chief exceeded his authority by trying to delay the Obama administration’s rule requiring oil and gas companies to track and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement issued on Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that, by dramatically changing course with respect to ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA’s obligation to cooperate with states in a comprehensive process of timely implementation of the new standards.
“In previous administrations, the EPA was often unable to meet the deadlines, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others, and discussed deadlines in the course of settling the case,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA at his previous post.
“We don’t believe in regulation through litigation, and we take the timing seriously.
We also take seriously our statute and the power it gives us.”
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt may at some point re-use its "postponement powers and other statutory powers" to ensure that the rules "jcyjdfys on a clear track and on all available information".
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader overhaul of the rules on ozone.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, seeks to delay the implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on the issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states that filed suit against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
“The EPA’s change of course after our lawsuits is an important victory in the fight for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by the smog that is covering their cities,” Schneiderman said.
California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia joined the lawsuit.
Ground-level ozone occurs when conventional pollutants from machinery, power plants, oil and chemical plants, and other sources enter the atmosphere in response to sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in people sensitive to it, leading to thousands of premature deaths per year.
Health advocates and environmentalists welcomed the unexpected shift in the course of Pruitt.
“It’s sad to think about how much pressure it took to achieve this completely logical step from the person who’s tasked with protecting the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to resist the Trump administration’s ideological campaign and protect those who pollute the air and their special interests.”
