Murder of Morse Ford: Activists Lose Lynch Trials on Stage to Call for Justice
In 1948, Ford Mercury drove past spectators in the village of Monroe, Georgia, and roared toward the small Mors Ford Bridge.
When the car, which had four black passengers and a white driver, approached the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked her way.
The main man - a middle-aged man in a thin striped suit - stretched out a cigar and looked through the windshield.
Those who sat inside trembled with fear.
"We need this nigger, Roger!" the man said.
"Get him out of the car!"
The piercing screams broke the silence as the young black man was pulled from the front seat.
Fortunately, this terrible scene, which took place on July 22nd, is just a production.
But when Roger's neck was thrown in a loop, almost all the spectators really took their breath away.
Since 2005, activists have been returning to the Mors Ford Bridge to re-lose the night in 1946 when puppeteers lynched two black couples — Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and May Murray Dorsey.
No one was convicted of these murders.
“It’s amazing that in all these years no one has been arrested — even though we see them around us; even though we know who they are,” says Tyron Brooks, who helped organize the production.
“It’s a stain on our history and it’s a stone on our souls.”
Brooks, 71, is a former congressman from Georgia who has been fighting for human rights his entire life.
For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the people of Monroe that injustice has never been rectified.
“We want investigations, we want closures, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice,” he says.
“We cannot move to healing and reconciliation until justice is done.”
The coroner covers the body of one of the victims of the lynching at Morse Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI materials obtained by the NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of participating in the lynching.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although the suspects remained at large for decades, human rights activists say that the city has always been well aware of two related motives of the lynchings: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling allowed black citizens for the first time to vote for the primaries to be held that summer.
Around the same time, according to the FBI, a black supporter, Roger Malcolm, struck a knife in a fight with Barnett Hester, a white landowner, apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says that rumor has it that Hester slept with Malcolm Dorothy's wife, and that the baby she was supposed to give birth to was not from her husband.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a large white landowner, paid $600 in bail to free Malcolm from prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But when they drove out of prison and approached the Mors Ford Bridge, a mob of lynched men surrounded the car.
“It turns out that he organized and commanded the murders of Harrison,” the FBI said in a report.
“It is also obvious that there was a conspiracy between state and city law enforcement agencies that not only took part in the killings, but also destroyed the evidence and concealed the identities of the witnesses.”
Brooks calls it short.
“It was an attack on the right to vote,” he says.
“They were all killed to send a signal to black people in the city: if you register and vote, you will be the same.”
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Greene has been directing the annual play, reproducing that lynching at the Mors Ford Bridge.
Its spectacle is vivid, it captures the audience and tells the story of the deep racism that many would like to consider no longer exists in America.
It’s hard to look at and even harder to turn away, but Green believes that’s what matters.
“We don’t want to talk about Lynch’s courts because they show us our own ugliness,” she says.
“But I can’t build a relationship with you if you don’t hear me or hear what I’ve been through.”
Rehearsals of this year's performance began in June, and on the first day almost 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest blacks - gathered in the room and listened to a review of the play, polished over the years.
Wade Marbo was the director with Greene.
He played the role of the main member of the clan for several years, but says that the role never got easier.
“I feel like I’m messed up because that’s not the person I am,” Marbo says.
“But I think it’s very important to remember this story because we don’t want to go back to that time.”
In the room, actors Darius Bradshaw and Nick Rascon, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, repeat their roles.
The show begins with Malcolm, angry that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Screams Raskona in response.
It's a hit.
And at the same time, all (at least all black actors) are outraged.
Green laughs louder than anyone.
"What is it?" asks Ascona.
He's worried and confused.
Am I overplaying?
“No,” Greene said with a laugh.
“I just don’t think the whites were saying ‘nigga’ then.”
"Yes," one of the black performers laughed.
"You've got to make a solid 'R'."
And so the energy in the room changes: discomfort is replaced by a sense of companionship.
Everyone must do everything right, not only for the sake of the play, but also for the sake of the memory of the four people killed.
The scene begins first.
This time, when Rascona speaks the word to the letter "n", it turns out to be clear and sharp.
No one laughs.
The show ends abruptly and quickly.
Screams, shots, and then silence.
The woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of the actors and performs the sad song of Billy Holiday "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted by a word.
In a hundred yards from her, half a hundred spectators wipe away tears and sweat from their eyes.
The audience is almost the same number of blacks and whites.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York to watch the show; many live right next door.
They all endured Georgia’s heavy spirit for nearly eight hours while Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the Malcolm and Dorsey graves.
Until that moment, the killings were only a story, but now that they are standing in the same place where they lynched people, it seems that their ghosts live right in the air.
When the last note of the song stops, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Children bend to their heads, touch the paint that depicts blood, and still bodies and whisper something to each other.
“They’re not really dead,” one little boy mumbles, as if to remind himself of it.
In a few minutes, Green thanks the audience, and suddenly it's over.
The actors drop the ropes from their necks and wipe away the tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, the man in the suit who played the main puppeteer.
Nick Rascona hugs two other actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional load of the show finally fell on him.
"It's all right," whispered one of the women.
“We know you have a good heart.
You had a reason for that.”
Later, the audience will sit down to dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta vividly discusses the show with a black couple they have just met.
Deniza Daplinski is struggling to find the words to describe what she feels after the performance.
“It’s hard to listen to these horrible, horrible words and actions... people who look like you and who do it because they look like you,” she says.
“After that, I think lynchings are still happening,” she adds, “only now it’s called shooting by the police.”
In the other corner of the room, Tyron Brooks, who remembers his work as a human rights defender, received general attention.
He says he has already started planning for next year’s show.
“The production inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we’ve experienced, but also teaches us,” he says.
“Because if you don’t learn from this lesson, it can happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it.”
