Judges offer protection from presidents
The Presidential Human Rights Council (HRC) on behalf of Vladimir Putin has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The SHRC proposes to limit the powers of the presiding officers of the courts and to introduce their discretion.
For the courts of appeal and cassation instance, the SPC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also present its proposals in the framework of the presidential mandate.
The HRH has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the HRH on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the President gave after meeting with the members of the Council.
At the meeting with the members of the council on December 8, 2016, discussed, among other things, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as the problems of public control in the places of detention of citizens (see "<0xD0><0x9A>" of December 9).
The result of the work of the HRH was 25 proposals, which concern both the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and the detection of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the court presidents to increase the independence of other judges.
If the candidate for the post of judge has successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, then the president of the court, in the opinion of the HRH, must submit it to the appointment, without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the President of the right to distribute cases for consideration among judges.
To do this, experts admit, can be a specially written computer program.
Also, the HRH believes that the chairman is not entitled to "predetermine the results of the qualification certification of the judge, initiate his involvement in disciplinary responsibility, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments."
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to "the election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "give them powers for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation".
Now all the presidents of the courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president at the presentation of the president of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the HRH proposes to re-organise appeals and cassation in courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRH says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of individual courts of appeal and cassation not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts."
Experts take as a basis the practice of arbitration courts.
There are "court districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee a greater independence from regional officials, who find it difficult to use "telephone law".
The World Court of Human Rights proposes to strengthen the participation of people’s judges to consider certain “categories of civil and administrative cases”.
For example, on the deprivation of parental rights, on the restoration to work, on the protection of honor and dignity, on the deprivation of driving rights, etc.
"These are only our proposals," said the member of the HHRC, a judge of the Constitutional Court in the resignation of Tamar Morshchakov.
She also recalled that the mandate of the President concerned not only the HRH, but also the Supreme Court (SC), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time to fulfill the order at the Armed Forces (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in Russia, the Chairman of the Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev must until September 1.
Living a high life: a half-story and clever design techniques turned this small apartment in Earls Court into a spacious apartment
Joan Lee, a former real estate banker, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is located on the first floor of a nice typical house in the style of Queen Anne, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not collect her things and did not move again.
“I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge on a much larger square,” Joan says.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price the same day.”
Since the first viewing, the apartment with an area of 1000 square feet has undergone a complete reconstruction.
Originally it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complicated layout – to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-floor to squeeze the maximum benefit out of the generous height of the ceilings.
“I wanted high ceilings, large windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill’s Duck & Shed architectural and design studio to use the 12.5-foot-tall ceilings to create a home that would not only be a successful project, but would suit Joan’s life.
The ceiling was not high enough to arrange two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a half-story where one could stand in full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to deal with the brief.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We had to arrange the rooms so that they were one above the other, and we didn’t have to bend.
It was necessary not just to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed to use the premises from above and below.”
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-sized rooms one above the other in a dedicated space – and much more interesting.
From the half-floor through a vintage copper light window from Retrouvius opens a view of the chic living room at the bottom.
Mirror furniture with gold finish, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures from Serge Muy set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space, and light.
A short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, a mirrored protective panel appears as a window to another room.
At the entrance, mirror cabinets are used to store all Joan's dishes.
To create a feeling of a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can fence the kitchen when not in use.
There is nothing new in the kitchen.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a moving up door, as in a garage.
“Engineering art was involved here,” Erfan told about the reinforced steel of the wooden-fiber shield door.
“It’s equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.”
Thanks to the reasonable use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and improved layout.
“Ultimately, the floor area is exactly what you’re going to sell, that is, what your property is valued for,” Erfan says.
“Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the floor area.”
Here they were able to increase the area of the floors, using quality materials that give the space a touch of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help to create an emotional connection with the home,” says Erfan.
“No one falls in love with the wiring in the walls.
It’s important, but it doesn’t hurt the strings of our hearts.”
This serves as evidence that due to good design and increased metering, an apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
