The brothers are fighting for a real estate empire worth more than $500 million.
The two brothers are fighting for one of the largest empires in the state of Victoria in a real estate trade worth more than $500 million – forty years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former Carlton Football Club director and developer Colin de Lutes lives in Turac Palace through three doors from his younger brother Paul, who filed a lawsuit against him in the Supreme Court over the division of possessions and assets.
Paul wants to leave the family business since 2014, but the Supreme Court is still in a heated dispute over the terms of the divorce.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars bought since their family bought a store on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew into a network of 160 retail outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the De Lutys family’s list of possessions today includes office buildings, construction sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, Gold Coast apartments and Mount Buller, and shopping malls in the suburbs.
By arrangement with his late father, Colin, whom Paul describes as the "leading driving force and dominating personality" of the De Lutys family, owns about two-thirds of the company's assets, and Paul owns about one-third.
According to the court, this means that Colin owns 316 million and Paul owns 176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling block for Paul.
“The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property,” he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
Last Friday, after several unsuccessful attempts at reconciliation, the first hearings in the Supreme Court took place.
The brothers are now arguing over who will control the existing business - from which, according to Paul, Colin excluded him.
Colin claims that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of some facilities.
In testimony given by Colin at the beginning of the trial, he says he hopes to resolve the dispute.
“My Italian roots make me consider the family a top priority,” he wrote.
The court costs are rising like a snowball: hundreds of pages of depositions, emails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer have been added to the case; both sides have attracted the best-known lawyers, including the royal lawyer Allan Myers, and the best uncles.
Mrs. De Lutes and her late husband Luigi were immigrants from Italy; from the late 1950s they ran milk bars and gastronomes, and in the early 1970s they bought a store in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood, where Colin opened his first family-owned jeans store.
Colin says he launched Westco when he was “in the last grades of school, and Paul was a boy (about 10 years old) at the time.”
Anna De Lutis says that they and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to hand over their possessions to their sons without conflict.
“Luiji often told me that he didn’t want the brothers to be tried in court,” she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutys group of companies; Colina says that Mark received $10 million when he left the business and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were “dissatisfied with the financial conditions of their office.”
Colin was not a public figure, though he was a former member of the AFL club board of directors and, according to Eddie McGee’s 2015 biography, the TV star’s best friend.
Fairfax Media on Friday contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers.
Colin only replied with a text message that, since the case had not yet been heard in court, "I really have nothing to say."
“I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul has decided to file a lawsuit against me and to shake the name of our family in court,” he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in his testimony that he was trying to satisfy his brother’s demands.
“Our father would not like to see us arguing in court,” he said, adding that he “still hopes to resolve the conflict.”
On Friday, that hope seems to have dissipated.
“The decision on our case will soon be made by the court,” Colin wrote.
The new head of the Trump apparatus plans to limit the receipt of information to the president.
Others tried to do so and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
In that case, he will be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information coming to President Trump, including news reports from the media, in hopes of keeping the chief in a more calm state.
