Italy is tightening its tone with regard to NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs owned by rescue vessels in the Mediterranean Sea that they will not be able to continue their work unless they comply with the new rules governing their activities.
“If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities,” Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin daily newspaper Stampa.
Minniti’s warning came a day after Italian authorities confiscated a ship owned by German humanitarian organisation Jugend Rettet, on suspicion that its crew was in fact cooperating with human traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has worked for only a year, has refused to comment on the merits of the detailed charges brought against it by the Italian prosecutor Ambrose Cartosio.
