The Russian authorities have recently significantly intensified their policy on the Libyan direction, and with visits to Moscow, delegations of opposing Libyan parties attended.
The head of the Russian contact group on the intra-Lithuanian settlement under the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, the assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Dengov told “U”, what goals Moscow pursues in this region and who it is betting on.
Almost nothing is known about the Libya contact group you are leading.
Here, let's say, the contact group on Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
Here is the veil of mystery.
What exactly do you do, what goals do you pursue?
The contact group was established at the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Deputy of the Duma from Chechnya.
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker "Mehanik Chebotarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board.
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma, was created, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
How did you manage to lead it?
Since I have been working in Libya since 2008, I have been asked to lead the group.
Our activity was not limited to the liberation of sailors from the "Mechanics of Chebotarev".
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all the main groups opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - and from Tripoli (where the recognized UN government led by Faiz Sarraj is based - "the"), and with Tobruk (the residence of the parliament that opposes the government and supports Marshal Haftali).
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metiga (Vice-Prime Minister of Libya - "<0xD0><0x9A>"), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I would like to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with either side of the conflict, we are in dialogue with everyone.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
There are now five people in the contact group.
Among them are people who have experience working in power structures, including in the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to introduce to the group of specialists by region, representatives of the Institute of the Middle East RAS.
No one is permanently in Libya from our staff, there is no need for this yet.
Is there now in Libya Russian military advisers, instructors.
And if so, whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the conversations and publications about this are not true.
But in your contact group, former military personnel are...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or cities such as Misurata (where militia units are based, which played a role in the ousting of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and significantly intensified in subsequent years) are closed to us.
We arrived in Missouri in January of this year.
We were scared, told that there were all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the role of Islamists there.
In Misurata, we met with all the representatives of the detachments that were engaged in the destruction of ISIS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was taken away from the militants of the banned in Russia "Islamic State" - "U").
We wanted to see them, to get to know these people, to check the information that they were the ones who played a decisive role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, and not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these merits to himself.
And what conclusion did you come to?
Has not the Islamic State in Libya defeated Haftar?
He didn't do that.
Haftar was conducting operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And the IS in Sirte were fought by structures that obeyed the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited to Russia people who carried out this anti-terrorist operation.
And they came - the visit was extended from 19 to 23 April this year, the Libyan delegation was accepted in the Council of the Federation, in the Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Rosgvardia.
You, as we understand, are in all Libyan regions and probably imagine the moods of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections that Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj reached at the end of July in Paris?
Or again, as has happened many times in the past, agreements will be broken, hostilities will resume, the parties will try to seize power alone?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, both leaders have been extremely negative about each other.
As for Russia's position...
They often write and say that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe in it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misurata, and Haftar was on board the Russian aircraft carrier “Admiral Kuznetsov” that day.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misurata, they did not believe in coincidence.
We were told, “You must be very brave people who came to us today.”
But our task is to show that we are not only supporting Haftar, we are engaging in dialogue with all key actors in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar have been in contact.
Does mutual understanding with Russian partners on a human, emotional level facilitate the fact that he studied twice in the USSR?
And, by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
If he knows Russian, it is very relative.
But what he has learned from us, of course, facilitates dialogue with him.
And not just with him, by the way.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misurata, we meet generals who have studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And they speak Russian very well.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent they are nostalgic for it.
Do you think that an immediate lifting of the arms embargo imposed on Libya is likely?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but, as I have already said, we do not take sides in this conflict and would not like to arm one at the expense of the other.
We would like everyone to be on an equal footing.
As for the arms embargo, there are constant calls from the Libyans for Russia to somehow facilitate its removal.
The process of drafting a constitution is now being actively promoted in Libya.
We hope that the parties will come to compromise decisions, will reach an internal consensus.
Then the elections should be held, which was also mentioned at the meeting of Saraj and Haftar.
If the elections are held and the legitimate power is finally elected (and now neither side has such a status), then the question of lifting the arms embargo can be put in the UN Security Council.
To raise this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
The other day, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees floating from Libya, feels left to chance by its EU allies.
In this situation, can Moscow help Italian partners by using its links with Libyans?
How realistic is it, for example, that Haftar’s troops will establish control over the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers transporting immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need Russia’s support because Moscow is in dialogue with both Haftar and Saraj, Misurata and the south of the country.
And in this issue, the tribes in southern Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about the Southerners cutting off the flow of migrants on long-distance approaches?
That is, conditionally speaking, were the buses that Nigerian migrants are travelling on were turned back?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help unite the South in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes of the South.
But first, we would like to see unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia law in the country.
How many radical views does he hold?
Will this not be an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But there are Islamists in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country – moderately Islamic, open to the world.
He is also actively fighting terrorists.
Why does he have such a reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, where there is legislative, executive and judicial power.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in us not going there.
And we mixed them all the cards and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has concluded an agreement on cooperation with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
The director of NOC Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosneft’s head Igor Sechin concluded the deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
Two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I think it's resold.
What are Russia’s economic interests in Libya?
The plans include re-signing contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
We are talking, in particular, about previous agreements in the field of transport (railway construction), energy (electricity) and a number of others.
Do Libyans have anything to pay for?
Well, they have oil.
That is, as in the case of Iran, it is a scheme "oil in exchange for services"?
I do not know what the scheme will be, I do not directly deal with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are, in fact, engaged in peacemaking.
For us, the main thing is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to agree among themselves so that they can establish order and Libya cease to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task – to help the Libyan people and to extort terrorists from there.
Do you have data on the presence in Libya (now or earlier) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to date no one from Russia and other countries of the former USSR is there.
He said he had about 50,000 phone records of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya - "U") and Russian speech does not sound there.
What kind of countries are these fighters from?
I don’t want to go into those details.
Then we will formulate the question differently.
How many of the Islamist militants in Libya are Libyans themselves?
There are practically no Libyans among them, they are no more than 5%.
The rest are newcomers.
Can Moscow hold internal negotiations on the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have declared their readiness to come again - to Moscow or to Grozny.
When can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say now.
There are still several visits to be made, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of the negotiations.
