Michelle Carter Sentenced for Instigating Conrad Roy's Suicide
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for inciting her boyfriend Conrad Roy to commit suicide by texting and making phone calls.
Michelle Carter, now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months of her term in jail and another 5 years of probation.
Carter was convicted in June of the involuntary manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father said in a hearing on Thursday: “My family was killed by grief.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain at large until the appeal.
She was threatened with a maximum term of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, wearing red pants and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing, clasping his hands and lowering his eyes.
“She killed Conrad Roy with her actions,” the prosecutor told the court.
“She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She did not accept responsibility,” she said.
“She didn’t show any remorse.”
But Carter’s lawyer said it was “a tragic case that she deeply regrets.”
Judge Lawrence Monis said, however, that in his opinion, her “age, level of maturity, or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions.”
The prosecutor read Roy’s mother Lynn Roy’s statement, which reads: “Not a day has passed that I have not mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I’m doing – I’m trying to support his sisters despite all the pain that will stay with us forever.”
Sister Roya Kamdin Roy said that she is constantly haunted by the thought that she will never be able to attend his wedding or become the aunt of his children.
“To hide the person who has always been with me since my birth is the pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life,” she said.
This case appears to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would provide for the responsibility of counsel for a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case caught the attention of the entire country when it became known that he had been pushed to suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, I don't know many ways to eat," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before she committed suicide, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad" and "You just have to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to gain attention through Roy's death, and banned her from communicating with the press to keep her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of the lawyers on this matter are divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British flatmate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
The 30-year-old Knox published in the Los Angeles Times her own opinion, which stated: "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
