The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid the enemies.
At first glance, it looks like a statue, although terrifying.
The researchers said that the first found remains of an incredible rhino-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner survived so well that experts called it “The Mona Lisa among the dinosaurs.”
It survived so well that they were even able to determine that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown—and say that he had, in a way, a “dark past.”
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as “the most well-preserved of the Tyraeophore in the history of the finds and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world.”
This fossil is a newly found specimen of a nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good condition has stunned researchers who call him “really wonderful.”
This herbivore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the finds, according to articles in the National Geographic magazine.
He was found by Sean Fank while he was working at Sancor's Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed to be different from the surrounding rock, and decided to look more closely.
