“It’s just a little sneeze, and you can almost believe he’s asleep,” said lead author Caleb Brown, a research fellow at the Royal Tyrell Paleontological Museum, where the creation is being demonstrated.
“It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaur specimens – the Mona Lisa among dinosaurs.”
By studying his skin, the researchers found that it was herbivorous, despite the fact that it was covered with armor and resembled a walking tank, apparently exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerful armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective paint, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow him to merge more quickly with the surrounding environment and avoid encounters with enemies, experts say, suggesting he was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old creature, belonging to the Nodosaurus family, was widely reported in the press in May, and is now on display at the Royal Tyrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of museum worker Mark Mitchell, one of the participants of the group, who spent more than 7,000 hours for his painstaking excavation.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international group of scientists to document the drawing and shape of the shells and armor plates on his body.
They found a protective paint, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its lower side.
Although the protective paint is well distributed, the discovery came as a surprise, because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is significantly larger than the size of the currently living animals with the protective paint.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred to disguise confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with a protective coat of paint — such as deer, zebras, or armored personnel carriers — are much smaller in size and more affordable prey, indicating that nodosaurs had to fight hard for survival.
“The serious threat from predators to a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous the predatory dinosaurs of the Melo period were,” Brown said.
The chemical analysis of organic compounds in the dinosaur’s scales also suggests that its skin should have been reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study an animal looking for information about its life, including the preserved contents of its digestive tract, to find out what it ate during its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was taken to the sea, where it sank and its back lay down to the bottom of the ocean.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and rivers and oceans were likely to have spread far deeper into the land than they are now.
“This nodosaur is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, and at the same time fully preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original shape of the animal,” Brown said.
“As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it did then, in the Early Cretaceous period.
You don’t have to use your imagination to recreate it, you just have to sneeze a little, and you can practically believe that he’s asleep.”
The Cretaceous period is an era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs, standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
