She put off the phone, and later that evening returned to tweets that people were going to the Canfield Drive.
There were photos of a signal tape and screaming people and a man claiming to be Brown’s father holding a poster with the words: “Ferguson policeman just killed my unarmed son!”
She watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another policeman, she said, picked up a rifle stick and said, “I’m going to kill all of you... animals!”
"It's a non-standard situation," Ferrel said at the time, according to her own memories.
“This is not a murder like the ones we are used to and can call typical.
At that moment, I felt cold.
I was angry and crying.”
She took the ticket for the return flight and flew home the next day.
Landing at 11 p.m., she took her six-year-old daughter from her father’s house and decided that they would both go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrel and Ferguson over the next almost three years has become the subject of a new documentary, Whose Streets?, which will be released on August 11.
It’s a story about survival and protest, about love and loss, strength and resilience from the perspective of people living in the community and filling the streets, demanding answers.
While Ferrel was on her way to Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a flower dress and a wreath of flowers, they recalled a conversation they had had countless times before this morning, “about the experiences of black people and their situation.”
She recalls saying, “Do you remember how I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We're going to Ferguson right now because a policeman killed an 18-year-old boy, and that was wrong."
“I couldn’t help but take her,” Ferrel said later.
“What is happening today is the culmination of what happened before.
She needs to know about it, see it, and grow up on it.
She must not only be well versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of experience of blacks and their situation and what we must do to be free to be free.
Even if I manage to provide her with an environment in which she herself will not face obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would have done her a bad favor if I had protected her from that.”
When they arrived in Ferguson, the first stop they made was at South Florissant Road, on a site across the road from a police station that had become something of a tent camp, while activists were waiting for reports of Officer Darren Wilson’s final non-indictment.
There, Ferrel and his daughter joined a local entrepreneur who cooked lunch packages.
They collected the packages and helped distribute them to the protesters.
Little by little, Ferrel found a new type of activism in his mind.
“My activism has completely changed since August 9,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Association of Sanitary Students, representing national minorities, and engaged in food justice and health inequality among black communities.
“I had no experience as an organizer.
It came by itself.”
A few weeks later, at an evening demonstration, Ferrel met Saba Folayan, one of his co-directors.
Folayan said she and her main operator, Lucas Alvarado-Ferrer, “just wanted to document” the events.
Ferrel came up with the question: “Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story that you can play on?”
This skepticism was fueled by numerous people, often white, who came to the community to benefit from its pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, “We’ve heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson don’t get the spotlight, and we wanted to do it differently.”
By that time, Folayan had already teamed up with her co-director, Damon Davis, a local artist known for her activism on death row issues.
His participation aroused a sympathy for the project with Ferrel and six other locals, with whom the team of the project "Whose Streets?" kept in touch during the years after Brown's murder.
“In this documentary, no one speaks for us or with us, we speak for ourselves,” Davis said.
“It was the most important thing for me how these people are going to be represented, because that’s how I’m going to be represented.”
And although the project’s goal was not to focus on Ferrel’s experience at all – in an effort to show that the movement “is not about a savior leader, but about how the community unites,” as Folayan said – it turned out to be the most open of the film’s participants.
As a result, “Whose Streets?” suddenly reveals the personal aspects of Ferrel’s life, such as how she fell in love and married his wife.
“I felt naked,” Ferrel said, laughing as she recounted how I first saw the finished product.
“But I understood that when you do that kind of work and humanize black people, there has to be some level of vulnerability.”
In addition, Ferrell’s story again discusses and emphasizes the role of black homosexual women in the broader context of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement — those who created the hashtag #BlackLivesMatter on social media after the 2012 murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin — have attributed themselves to homosexuals.
“Black gay women in leadership positions support this whole movement,” says Ferrel, “and it’s all because we’re constantly fighting on several fronts.
Black gay women have to bear all of this burden.”
Folayan agreed with the claim, noting that “the movement is actually supported by black women and a host of gay black women.”
However, she insists that "this is not a case of positive discrimination" and that Ferrel was not chosen as the central character of the film because of its distinctive features.
“She was the person who awakened that energy,” she said.
"On the other hand, it's no coincidence that she was in the foreground because when she was in the
You can feel her energy through the screen.”
Meanwhile, Ferguson has long been without a movie camera, but there are complex racial ties between the community and the police.
Ferrel will be on probation for another two-and-a-half years for shutting down the highway during the demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the place, which she calls home, simply: “Bardak”.
She's still holding on to the speech she learned when she took to the streets of Ferguson full three years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We have to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.”
