The emergence of similarity: the artist creates portraits using the DNA of Chelsea Manning
In the center of the hall in the Friedman Gallery in New York from the ceiling on the wire hang the faces of people - white, black and brown, all somewhat elusively similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by the artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek strokes and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning has sent in cuts from Fort Lawnworth Prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the notorious transmission of confidential diplomatic cables on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called "The Rise of Similarity".
This is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and a famous dissident, whom Barack Obama commuted just three days before the end of his presidency.
Analysing using a computer program of DNA obtained from Manning and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of individuals who could be in people with such a genome, Dewey-Harborg created a deep, though not easy to perceive manifesto, dedicated not only to the plasticity of these DNAs and to the various ways in which they could be represented.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has openly said she considers herself a woman since she was a teenager, was sentenced in 2013 to 20 episodes, including six violations of the Espionage, Computer Fraud and Stealing Act.
Her photographs in prison were inaccessible, so only one of her photographs was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie, in which Manning, in a platinum shade of wig, clearly feeling uncomfortable, sits behind the wheel of a car; with this photograph she and began to associate.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg successfully completed her 2012 project “Visions of Strangers”.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as pickles and chewing gum, separating DNA from this garbage and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
“They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article,” Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of a new exhibition for the press.
At the time, Chelsea could not be visited and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait made of her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book called “Suppressed Images,” illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which depicted how in the future the president would ease Chelsea’s punishment and be able to visit the exhibition in person.
The fact that Obama really decided to release Manning just days after the book came out was a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a Kansas military prison.
There’s something deep and strong about the fact that the exhibition opens right now when Donald Trump declares war on people revealing secret information in the government and invents new ways to inflame the animosity he’s meant to soften on Twitter.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked if all this coincided in time, she said that “nothing happens by chance.”
In a statement, the artist wrote on the wall of the gallery, a huge Manning signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a point above the “i” in her name) calls for an end to “an automatic division based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture.”
On the opposite side is its mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of pencils C, G and A.
Including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist puts it scientifically), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how amazingly similar we all are, at least in terms of our biological structure.
“I hope to explain to people that our genome doesn’t define what we are, how open genetic data is to interpretation, and how subjective it is,” Dewey-Harborg said; her 2007 video work “False Memories” is also exhibited here.
“DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here.”
The last part of the exposition, which fits in one room, is the novel mentioned above in the comics.
On it, King Kong-style Manning appears above the U.S. Correctional Facility building with a loudspeaker in hand.
“If they kill your speech, they will win,” it says.
"Therefore, never be silent."
“This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me,” says the artist, who hails from Philadelphia.
"I still have ants on my skin when I talk about it."
Manning has not yet seen the exhibition in person – as it was vividly depicted in the comics – but when she arrives, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacrums gathered like crowds of protesters.
This is also done intentionally, like everything at the exhibition up to the height (5"2, the growth of Manning), on which the pencil was drawn genetic haplogroups.
“I used to hang them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people,” Dewey-Harborg says of the portraits.
“I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, like the movement that stood behind its liberation.”
