Startups that will help your company not to become another “Uber”
Amy Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among employees of her startup in the field of e-commerce, but the surveys did not work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or, worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees didn’t trust the process.
“He’s never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, who runs Madison Reed, a 75-person hair care e-commerce company based in San Francisco.
She turned to third parties for help.
Now a new kind of start-ups in the field of work with staff is emerging, which help companies to find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to make express surveys, address specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases allow informants to be targeted.
“We now have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, but where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Glint, a Redwood City startup whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she has achieved a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel in three years of using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and shows in a visual form, which units have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies are becoming increasingly aware that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become another “Uber” who was involved in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive situation in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like Glint, it’s a desire to control the situation – an opportunity for a profitable business.
According to the Internet portal “Let’s talk about payment”, dedicated to financial technologies, the industry of global management, regulation and compliance by 2020 can cost more than 118.7 billion dollars.
The Denver, Colorado-based Convercent startup, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid Uber’s declining reputation.
The company has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Recently, “Uber” appeared among customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send custom-made surveys of staff opinions, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the management.
“The court of public opinion has seized power from the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is mishandling employees or behaving unethically, even if the inspectors don’t intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of customer boycotts, employee outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a chain of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, has been using Convercent for more than a year to make sure employees are aware of the rules and procedures, and to offer an easy way to contact the company’s head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to search for a phone number or email from the head office, file a formal complaint and hope to take it seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, chief legal officer at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using the “Convert” service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay – can be detected and addressed more quickly.
“I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the employee situation,” said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
“And we protect our shareholders from lawsuits with employees.”
According to Quinland, the companies began to take ethics, values and employee engagement more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen’s accounting firm collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron Affair.
But it wasn’t until “social media became widespread” that the companies realized they wouldn’t be able to keep their dirty underwear from spreading the virus online.
“Before we started using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both “Glint” and “Convert” offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
It is a business model and an opportunity that has received the approval of venture investors who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company’s total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company’s total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising, given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than they used to.
In markets with stiff competition, such as Silicon Valley, high wages, and interesting projects, this is just the minimum needed.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and valued, and that they dedicate their time to a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in a company, feel that they are heard, and that the work they do brings results, they are more trying to make such a company successful,” says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Glincent and Convercent are used.
Investors get income when the business of companies from their portfolio goes well; the business of companies goes well when employees are loyal and engaged.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it’s no surprise that they find support.
According to experts on culture in the workplace, it is important to have data on employee involvement.
But the data is useless until the company’s trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can create the impression that changes are coming.
And if the changes don’t come fast enough, or don’t come at all, disappointment may develop, and employees will lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you should be prepared to hold 4,000 interviews,” says Russell Ratt, president of consulting at Kotter International, which had to see companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go to the end, employees will be like, ‘Did you really hear me?
You don't care?
If you don’t care, why shouldn’t I care?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports a problem with Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees unhappy with the speed of decision-making and quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long run, this knowledge will help it to keep employees in an industry known for its high staff turnover.
“If you don’t try to create a culture of transparency, you’re going to lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
