The Castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells of the families who lived in Scotland; each story is illustrated by one of the young British artists – Isaac Lenkevich, Brianie May Smith, William Axley, Becky Palmer and Isabelle Grinber.
This is not the first book by Rhodes to be based on archival data: in 2014 he wrote Teeth of a Dead Man and Other Stories, a collection of British Library documents; this project unexpectedly touched him to the depths of his soul.
“I could have been scratched by just a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working on the Jacobites,” he says.
"It's the fingerprint of his finger."
And the letters always smell of smoke, because in those times the lights were on.
And in 300 years, in the future, you feel like you're there, too.
Oh, how I love the archives!"
For a person with such a passion for old papers, getting support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and living in a castle for four months (“Honestly, I got a bit stuck there”) seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the "new" Victorian castle, going through the archives and looking at numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that had lain in the ditch for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking with the foresters, gardeners and sometimes with artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Then, at night, he “drinked whiskey and sat down to write.”
The history of Scotty Castle is not very well studied, because the National Fund gained full access to it only in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hassy, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, employees were just starting to deal with the archive, which he describes as “what aristocrats have been doing for centuries”.
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring," says Rhodes, "but two families fought for this birch.
It happens, guys!”
In some stories, the castle collection becomes the starting point for wider explorations in English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
“There are reports of a rebellion that occurred at the castle in 1380, in a book called ‘The Knight Families of Kent and Sussex,’” Rhodes says.
“The Peasant Rebellion began in these places, and I thought the revolt was the right start.
Maybe they were connected?”
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle - for example, the "Priest", which tells of a Jesuit priest, whom the Darrelov family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Contrabandist", about the 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrel, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stoning the tomb (this was discovered a few years later when the tomb was excavated).
Darrely is Rods’s favorite family of all the people who lived in Scotty’s house: “The gentlemen seem to have been a perfect fraud, forever in debt, and spent money on things they couldn’t afford.
In different generations of men, the Darrels have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women – I imagine them to be the company of cute guys who know how to care for the heirs of great fortunes.
After completing his work at Rhodes Castle, he is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish Deaf, where he wrote a graphic novel about Eliamianm<0xC3><0xA4>ki – a place where there was a sanatorium at the beginning of the 20th century, and then it grew again in the forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he says.
“I felt something like this: Hell, I have to go back to real life.”
