Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help ease HVAC.
Red meat and chocolate are considered nightmares for your digestive tract.
But recent studies say the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help relieve symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects about 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to alleviate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid protein tryptophan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the intestines make sure that harmful microbes coming from food do not enter the body.
Cells that are able to trigger the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and at the same time not harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed in the direction of inflammation, this can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in the gut appear to increase the tolerance of the cell.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan — one of the building blocks of protein — to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have established a link between one species of bacteria — Lactobacillus reuteri — which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan was contained in the mice’s diet, the more of these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet may contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation of the environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barrag<0xC3><0xA1>nvas, studying the variety of immune cell tolerance, found that one group of test mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same line, but was contained separately, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice — communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that typically live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of mouse intestinal cells was sequenced, and six species of bacteria were found present in mice that had immune cells but were absent in mice that did not.
The mice, grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells, received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of fluid—without bacteria—to underdeveloped immune cells secreted from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice’s food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan level was reduced by half, the number of cells also dropped by double.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same cell tolerance as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is unknown whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans as well as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in the genes associated with tryptophan have been found.
She says, “Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can potentially lead to an expansion of their population."
