The disabled Anton Mamaev was given a fine
The Moscow court eased the sentence of disabled wheelchair user Anton Mamaev from four and a half years in prison to a fine of 200 thousand rubles.
Earlier, by the decision of the Timiryazev court, the convicted person was released from the SIZO.
At the same time, the Mosgorsud confirmed that the accused is a criminal, because he organized the robbery and abduction of a scooter from a former special forces fighter.
By its decision, the Moscow court relaxed the punishment of Anton Mamaev to 200 thousand rubles. fine.
"Mamayev is the organizer of the robbery, which also forms part of the crime, and, accordingly, such a person should be brought to criminal responsibility," said Ulyan Solopov, spokesman for the Moscow court.
In this case, the court took into account Mamaev's state of health, the facts of the case, the absence of aggravating circumstances.
In addition, the court applied Article 64 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation, according to which a punishment below the lower limit can be imposed.
As for Mamaev’s assistant Vasily Seroshtanov, the court did not establish the circumstances that would be the basis for changing the category of severity of the sentence and changing the sentence.
Anton Mamaev himself said that he remained dissatisfied with the decision of the Moscow court.
I'm disappointed with the court's decision.
The only legitimate solution would be an excuse to continue fighting for justice.
His lawyer Andrey Orlov did not rule out the appeal of the sentence in the cassation instance of the Moscow court and the Supreme Court.
“We will use all the levers up to the European Court of Human Rights,” he told RIA Novosti.
Recall, 28-year-old Muscovite Anton Mamaev, suffering from spinal muscular atrophy, became a figurehead of the criminal case in the fall of last year.
The disabled person claims that he bought a scooter from friends for 160,000 rubles, to then sell.
However, the owners of the scooter, including a former special forces fighter, said that the disabled and his assistant Vasily Seroshtanov seized their property, threatening to use violence.
On June 30, the Timiryazevsky District Court of Moscow sentenced Vasily Seroshtanov to three years of the colony, and Anton Mamaev to four and a half years of imprisonment with serving a sentence in the colony of the general regime (under Part 2 of Article 162 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
After the disabled person was placed in the SIZO, the Public Chamber, the Prosecutor General’s Office, the human rights commissioner under President Tatiana Moskalkova, joined the case.
As a result, in mid-July Anton Mamaev was released from SIZO by the decision of the same Timiryazev court.
The defense, in turn, appealed the decision of the first instance in the Moscow court.
The ONF will prepare a report on the environment for the President
The final “Forum of Action” of the All-Russian People’s Front (ONF) in 2017 will be devoted to environmental issues, a source in the ONF told Izvestiam and confirmed the head of the executive committee of the movement Alexei Anisimov.
According to him, according to the results of the forum, the "frontists" plan to prepare a report to the President on the problems of the domestic environment, as well as to propose a strategy for their solution.
The interlocutors of Izvestia in the ONF note that the report to the head of state will contain a "deep analysis" of the situation in all federal districts of the country.
According to Izvestia, the final forum of the ONF will be held in autumn.
The exact date of its conduct has not yet been determined - as a rule, it is adjusted to the schedule of the president, who is the leader of the movement and traditionally present at key events of the ONF.
The front held several interregional environmental conferences, one for two federal districts - in Rostov-on-Don, Kaliningrad and Kirov.
The result will be a conference in the capital of the Republic of Buryatia Ulan-Ude.
Based on the proposals that have been made and will be made at these events, we will form systematic proposals for solving environmental problems, - told "Izvestia" interlocutor in the ONF.
Co-chairman of the Central staff of the movement Olga Timofeeva, who heads the State Duma Committee on Ecology and Environmental Protection, said that the “frontists” will inform the head of state about the work carried out within the framework of the Year of Ecology in Russia.
The final environmental forum and the “Forum of Action” of the ONF are likely to be combined.
Over the year, we grew up with a powerful team of experts in the field of environmental problems, saw gaps in the legislation, stopped dozens of violations of the law.
All of this will be part of the report that we are preparing for the president as the leader of our movement.
In addition to this document, the "frontists" are also reporting on the work on priority projects of the ONF, - Olga Timofeeva told "Izvestiam".
According to her, a special representative of the head of state on environmental activities, ecology and transport Sergey Ivanov will be invited to the forum.
Previously, he had already participated in the work of the ONF Media Forum, which was held in St. Petersburg in April.
In a few months, the Year of Ecology will go down in history, and the most important thing to do today is to launch environmental mechanisms so that they work for many years.
So that these questions do not fall out of the agenda, - added Olga Timofeeva.
Andrei Kolyadin, Head of the Laboratory of Regional Policy of the Expert Institute of Social Research (EISI), noted that by raising environmental issues, the ONF operates in the direction of the presidential agenda.
Many things they offered as experts in various forums, and these initiatives received the support of the president, - said "Izvestiam" Andrei Kolyadin.
He stressed that to date, the economic potential of the environmental agenda cannot be excluded, which can give regions an additional impetus for development.
In the future, with the help of ONF, regions will be able to lobby not only for the solution of their environmental problems, but also for the development of ecotourism, the expert added.
The relevance of environmental issues was demonstrated by the “direct line” with Vladimir Putin in June.
In particular, the president was asked about the garbage dump in Balashikha (already closed) and about the coal dust in the port of Nahodka (a bill on the prohibition of open coal transshipment in settlements has already been developed, one of the authors is Olga Timofeeva).
Experts in the field of ecology believe that the legal basis for solving environmental problems in Russia as a whole is created, the issue is in the further law-enforcement practice, as well as in the position of civil society.
We need a clear implementation of the decisions taken by the state, - believes the head of the charity foundation "Ecology for All" Leonid Bochin.
Sergey Tsyplenkov, member of the HRH, head of the non-governmental organization Greenpeace of Russia, in a conversation with Izvestia, stressed that a responsible approach of society and business is needed to successfully solve environmental problems, and there are few legislative efforts.
As soon as society and business realize that solving environmental problems is a much more profitable step in the strategic perspective, the situation will change, - said Sergey Tsyplenkov.
The expert stressed that it is necessary to break the trend to the fact that the violation of environmental legislation is an economically advantageous solution for business.
The British inventor used a microchip to get into the house and car at the stroke of a hand
The British inventor became the first person in the country to have a microchip installed so that he could open the door of his house, enter the office and even start the car with a simple swipe of his hand.
Thirty-three-year-old Stephen Northam has implanted a tiny chip between his thumb and forefinger and now, through his firm BioTek, offers this service to firms and individuals who want to simplify their lives at the expense of technology.
He teamed up with Dr. Jeff Watson, an anesthesiologist-consultant from Royal in Winchester, to ensure that the implantation procedure was carried out in accordance with medical standards.
The technology is similar to a microchip that is fed to cats and dogs, and the procedure takes only 30 seconds.
Northam also replaces locks in homes and cars with chip-compatible locks at a price of <0xC2><0xA3>300 per lock.
The married father of one child has already installed the technology in his home and in his BMW Z4, which is launched when his hand is on the steering wheel.
Requisite for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House’s decision last month to bring a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn at an event dedicated to U.S. industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as “Marine One” when the president is on board, became a central element of the July 17 White House event that showcased U.S. construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and senior White House officials reviewed technology products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-made helicopter was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a truckloader from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the department in charge of the helicopter management, the White House Military Department ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or “FRAGO”, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the southern runway by accident.
“I just wanted you to make sure you’re aware because this is an unusual, widely publicized event,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his chief, the Marine Corps’ first deputy chief of aviation, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Meadow at about 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in an event scheduled for 3 a.m. and would remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the restrictions on working hours.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the security personnel of the unit remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records obtained by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether the second crew was required in the end.
Hatch's law prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 specified whether the event contradicted this resolution.
“Among other things, we asked if it was a violation of Hatch’s law, and we were told not to,” the commander wrote.
“You don’t seem to have anywhere to go,” the deputy chief replied.
The event “Made in America” was announced by the White House as an official event, and Hatch’s law did not apply to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the health care reform that was being drafted in the Senate at the time, and praised the attempts to regulate government decrees.
The use of aircraft known as “Marine One” and “Air Force One” for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But to ask them only in the interests of photo opportunity is unusual.
Trump has already been the subject of discussions in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with reports of complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
"The White House is delighted with the 'Made in America' show, which showcased products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," White House spokeswoman Lindsay Walters said in a statement.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the U.S. president’s transportation to the White House with an accuracy of up to one inch.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight made for the event “Made in America” was counted to the crew on account of the necessary training flights for a month.
The unit’s helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of “non-presidential support tasks.”
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of the company "Sikorsky" said that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the southern meadow.
HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Department of Defense’s hourly rates for the 2017 fiscal year, the Department of Defense’s refund rate for VH-3D is $24,380 per hour of flight.
In the records of the unit, it was recorded that the time of the aircraft in the air was 30 minutes in each direction from its airfield based at the Quantico Marine Air Base in Virginia.
The White House says the actual cost of using the helicopter is well below that rate.
“Calculating the value for taxpayers based on the approximate rate of compensation is completely wrong,” says Walters.
“These approximate rates include staffing, maintenance, and many other non-repayable costs that are included in annual appropriations.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by REND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of fuel, services and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated using a helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate this week things done in America,” Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
So, of course, it is appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the Southern Lawn during the event, but he certainly sat in the driver’s seat in a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of products.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” the president said, “I have three of them.”
Moscow will allocate grants for the resuscitation departments of city hospitals
Every year, grants "Saving lives" will be awarded to resuscitation and intensive care departments of capital clinics.
Funds are being made to encourage doctors and nurses.
