NBU reported the absence of buyers of the Ukrainian "daughter" of Sberbank
The National Bank of Ukraine (NBU) reported no applications for the purchase of the Ukrainian “daughter” of Sberbank.
This was reported by TASS on Friday, August 4, with reference to the representative of the press service of the NBU.
The NBU confirms that on August 3, 2017, a package of documents from the citizen of Belarus and Cyprus Victor Prokopeni for the approval of the indirect (through Paritetbank) acquisition of 100 percent of the shares of Sberbank was withdrawn.
"Documents from other potential investors for the purchase of Sberbank shares in the NBU have not been received," the statement said.
On August 3, Belarusian businessman Viktor Prokopenia withdrew the application for the purchase of the subsidiary structure of Sberbank.
On July 28, it became known that the National Bank of Ukraine refused to Russian businessmen Said Gutseriev and Grigory Guselnikov in the acquisition of the Ukrainian “daughter” of Sberbank.
The regulator justified its decision by the fact that the businessmen did not provide the necessary documents to verify their compliance with the requirements of the legislation of Ukraine.
Sberbank reported the sale of its Ukrainian “daughter” to Norvik Banka and a private Belarusian company in March this year.
The majority shareholder of the consortium was Said Gutseriev, son of Russian businessman Mikhail Gutseriev.
Sanctions against the “daughters” of five Russian banks in Ukraine, including Sberbank, were introduced in mid-March.
During the year, they are forbidden to withdraw capital from the country in favor of the mother organizations.
