The National Union of Unskilled, Municipal and Boiler Workers (GMB) is concerned about the investment at McVitie's factory in Glasgow
The union is demanding guarantees from the managers of McVitie’s cookie maker in connection with its long-term commitment to manufacturing at the Glasgow plant.
The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company has been silent on the issue of future investments at the Tolkien facility.
The factory, which produces, among other products, cookies Hobnobs and Rich Tea, employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, the owner of McVitie’s, said it had invested more than <0xC2><0xA3>5 million in the facility over the past few years.
The company adds that in the event of any changes in the work of the facility, employees and representatives of the trade union “learn about them first.”
In a letter to the head of the facility owned by the company, the Scottish branch of GMB demanded McVitie's response to concerns that funding would not be allowed to upgrade production lines.
Senior organizer Drew Duffy said: “The members of our union are deeply concerned that we cannot get clarity from the facility’s general manager on business needs and the investment plan for the future of Tolcross.”
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is great in local society and in Greater Glasgow; it is the most important pillar of decent work in the territory of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Thus, from the point of view of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, the rise of the subsistence minimum and the chronic decline of production, East End Glasgow desperately needs the prosperity of production at McVitie's factory.
According to a representative of Pladis, “The head of the Tolkien facility only yesterday received a letter from the Scottish branch of GMB, and the company will respond immediately, as we appreciate our constant cooperation with the employees and representatives of the union.”
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with GMB employees and representatives in Tolkros, where we openly discussed a number of issues.
We talked to employees about how all companies operating in the most competitive and unstable economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions – and this applies to all our facilities and activities – to remain competitive.
“In recent years, we have invested more than <0xC2><0xA3>5 million in our Tolcros facility, especially in production lines and improved functional performance.”
We are fully aware of the value of Tolkros as a production facility, and in case of any changes in work at this facility, employees and representatives of the trade union will be the first to know about this.”
Putin said that the authorities will not give instructions to Rosneft and Gazprom
Vladimir Putin said that the Kremlin and the Cabinet should connect to the issue of gas supplies to the Eastern Petrochemical Company (VNHC), but no one will give instructions to Gazprom, like Rosneft.
Thus, Russian President Vladimir Putin responded to the request of Igor Sechin to assist in resolving the conflicts that have arisen.
The Head of State noted that the relations between Rosneft and Gazprom should be resolved exclusively on the basis of market principles.
Earlier, the head of Rosneft, Igor Sechin, at a meeting on the implementation of large investment projects in the Far Eastern Federal District, said that the lack of agreement with Gazprom on gas for VNHK endangers the project implementation period.
Sechin noted that the dialogue with Gazprom on this issue continues.
“Gazprom offers to find gas resources from the perimeter of Rosneft, but we do not have such resources,” Sechin added.
Rosneft has asked for permission to use gas from the Kirin field of Gazprom, located on the Sakhalin shelf, for the Eastern Petrochemical Company.
In June, Gazprom said that negotiations on the issue are ongoing, and “there are no sharp corners there.”
Did PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar’s move three years ago?
